{
  "doc_id": "24357",
  "text": "2 /s; and F: 17 (6.0-28)%. Multivariate analyses showed ADC and D decreased with steatosis and F decreased with fibrosis (P < 0.05). Associations between DWI-estimated parameters and other histologic features were not significant: ADC: fibrosis (P 5 0.12), lobular inflammation (P 5 0.20), portal inflammation (P 5 0.27), hepatocellular inflammation (P 5 0.29), NASH (P 5 0.30); D: fibrosis (P 5 0.34), lobular inflammation (P 5 0.84), portal inflammation (P 5 0.76), hepatocellular inflammation (P 5 0.38), NASH (P 5 0.81); F: steatosis (P 5 0.57), lobular inflammation (P 5 0.22), portal inflammation (P 5 0.42), hepatocellular inflammation (P 5 0.59), NASH (P 5 0.07). Conclusion: In children with NAFLD, steatosis and fibrosis have independent effects on DWI-estimated parameters ADC, D, and F. Further research is needed to determine the underlying mechanisms and clinical implications of these effects. N onalcoholic fatty liver disease (NAFLD) has emerged as the most common cause of chronic liver disease in children in the United States. [CITATION_1] Currently, the clinical reference standard for evaluation of NAFLD and its progressive variant, nonalcoholic steatohepatitis (NASH), is histologic assessment. [CITATION_2] However, histologic assessment requires biopsy, which is invasive and carries risks including pain and bleeding. [CITATION_3] Therefore, quantitative noninvasive methods are desired for evaluation of NAFLD and NASH in children.-magnetic resonance imaging (MRI) diffusion-weighted imaging (DWI) is one promising noninvasive evaluative technique. DWI detects incoherent motion of water protons diffusing and perfusing through tissue. [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] This motion depends on tissue microstructure and is affected by degree of cellularity, [CITATION_6] volume of extracellular space, [CITATION_7] and composition of cellular membranes. [CITATION_8] Chronic pediatric liver diseases such as NAFLD can alter tissue microstructure, thereby affecting incoherent motion. [CITATION_9] [CITATION_10] DWI parameters are sensitive to incoherent motion and therefore may provide insight into microstructural alterations. Numerous studies have shown that DWI parameters are associated with fibrosis [CITATION_11] [CITATION_12] [CITATION_13] [CITATION_14] [CITATION_15] [CITATION_16] and inflammation [CITATION_17] [CITATION_18] [CITATION_19] in viral hepatitis. More recent studies have shown significant associations between some histologic features of NAFLD (steatosis, [CITATION_20] [CITATION_21] [CITATION_22] [CITATION_23] [CITATION_24] fibrosis, [CITATION_25] [CITATION_26] and inflammation [CITATION_27] and quantitative DWI parameters in adults. The generalizability of these findings to pediatric NAFLD is unclear, however, because the dominant pattern of NASH in children differs from that in adults. [CITATION_28] The pediatric pattern is characterized by portal inflammation and/or fibrosis without the ballooning degeneration and perisinusoidal fibrosis typical of adult NASH. [CITATION_29] The microstructural differences between pediatric and adult patterns of NASH may affect associations of histologic features and DWI parameters. Additionally, MRI is more difficult to perform in children due to variability in breath-holding capacity, body habitus, and exam tolerability. [CITATION_30] For these reasons the relationship between histology and DWI in children with NAFLD is uncertain. Therefore, this study evaluated associations between histologic features of NAFLD and estimated quantitative DWI parameters in children.",
