    {
      "citation_id": "[CITATION_1]",
      "span_text": "N onalcoholic fatty liver disease (NAFLD) has emerged as the most common cause of chronic liver disease in children in the United States.  Currently, the clinical reference standard for evaluation of NAFLD and its progressive variant, nonalcoholic steatohepatitis (NASH), is histologic assessment."
    },
    {
      "citation_id": "[CITATION_2]",
      "span_text": "Currently, the clinical reference standard for evaluation of NAFLD and its progressive variant, nonalcoholic steatohepatitis (NASH), is histologic assessment.  However, histologic assessment requires biopsy, which is invasive and carries risks including pain and bleeding."
    },
    {
      "citation_id": "[CITATION_3]",
      "span_text": "However, histologic assessment requires biopsy, which is invasive and carries risks including pain and bleeding.  Therefore, quantitative noninvasive methods are desired for evaluation of NAFLD and NASH in children.-magnetic resonance imaging (MRI) diffusion-weighted imaging (DWI) is one promising noninvasive evaluative technique."
    },
    {
      "citation_id": "[CITATION_4]",
      "span_text": "DWI detects incoherent motion of water protons diffusing and perfusing through tissue.   This motion depends on tissue microstructure and is affected by degree of cellularity,  volume of extracellular space,  and composition of cellular membranes."
